main event: A triangular-shaped object, bright white in color with a red dot in the center, was observed in the sky over Watertown, New York on March 10, 1953.
interesting points: The object turned small then large, as though it was turning.
The object was observed for about 6 minutes at an elevation of 50-55 degrees.
The sighting was initially reported as unidentifiable, with no attempt to rationalize it.
Radar tracking of the object by the 662nd AC&W Squadron was negative.
The sighting was eventually concluded to likely be the planet Venus.
sighted object: triangular-shaped bright white object with red dot
witnesses: multiple witnesses including a housewife, production engineer, and high school student
photographs: no, the report does not include any photographs
